<h1>Hotel Rooms</h1>

<p><a href="<?php echo $this->url('room/create'); ?>" style="background:#2c7a2c;color:#fff;padding:6px 14px;border-radius:4px;text-decoration:none;">+ Add Room</a></p>

<p>
    This page lists all rooms. Each <code>$room</code> is now a <strong>RoomEntity object</strong>
    (Lecture 22) — we call <code>getNumber()</code>, <code>getType()</code> etc. instead of
    accessing array keys like <code>$room['number']</code>.
</p>

<table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0;">
    <thead>
        <tr style="background: #2c7a2c; color: #fff;">
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Room #</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Type</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: right;">Price/Night</th>
            <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Actions</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <?php foreach ($this->rooms as $room): ?>
        <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;">
            <td style="padding: 10px;"><?php echo $this->escapeHtml($room->getNumber()); ?></td>
            <td style="padding: 10px;"><?php echo $this->escapeHtml($room->getType()); ?></td>
            <td style="padding: 10px; text-align: right;"><?php echo $room->getPrice(); ?> BGN</td>
            <td style="padding: 10px;">
                <a href="<?php echo $this->url('room/detail', array('id' => $room->getId())); ?>">Details</a>
            </td>
        </tr>
        <?php endforeach; ?>
    </tbody>
</table>

<p style="color: #666; font-size: 0.9em;">
    <strong>Full data flow (Lectures 20–22):</strong><br>
    RoomService initialises each room with <code>$room->exchangeArray($row)</code>
    (array → entity). The view calls <code>$room->getNumber()</code> etc. to read the values.
    In a real app, <code>$row</code> would come from Doctrine's EntityManager instead of
    hardcoded data.
</p>
